A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in the 'called' HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists test new compounds able to moderate the spread of HIV in the organism
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some available medicines already.
AIDS disease cannot be cured until now.
However, the life of patients may be significantly prolonged by a mixture of medicines that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the virus replication is not completely suppressed, the so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, medicines are no longer working.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of dominating the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metalocarborans have an effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metal carbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way from all the medications used today, and that is why they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, ‘better' compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the albumin of the virus.
Metal carbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyedral cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are bound by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A Traitor and Resistant Virus
