A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, caught renewed attention on Friday with the disclosure of a document that provides ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiations that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Developed by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not speak of how much money the rich countries would give to the poor to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of global temperature increase that political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, high representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 from 25 to 45 per cent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period from 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions from 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also stimulated the talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday was the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated the conversations last week.
The United States Special Climate Envoy, Todd Stern, rejected the claims that demand mandatory greenhouse gas emission cuts for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is adopting a tougher line with China, with regard to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make an agreement without the major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the U.S. top climate negotiator lacked "common sense", or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the U.S. would not help China economically to cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's main powers at stake, the fault lines have erupted both within the developing world, as well as between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rican delegate, said it's not surprising that the main powers are discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive looking to contain the large issuers responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who also works as a regional consultant on climate change in Mexico and Central America, for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that the talks will produce a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, prepared a proposal for a 24-page preliminary treaty early in the morning of Friday.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has "impacted political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and demand the action of emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency while delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the exceptional issues before the heads of government came to an agreement.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese deputy minister, descended from the aircraft and ran towards the Bella Center corridors, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, so that they could define the claims to be arbitrated during the next week.
