The Cunning of the Dinosaur
The Tawa finde had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal of two meters long and 1.50 meters tall running on the two strong back legs, had an elongated head with sharp teeth and curved, short arms with clutches in the form of a hose and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple million years later, this would not have been something special.
But Tawa finde was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the Science magazine on Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the spread and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we have found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, this is unprecedented for Triasic sediments, reports Randall Irmis member of the Utah Natural History Museum team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
During the excavation, the remains of five specimens were collected in total.
A finding confirms the theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the god of the Hopi Indian sun.
For Sterling Nesbitt is an exceptional finding: "The Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current current opinion, dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, the experts discuss, for example, when the sauries were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropodes among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropodes known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithischia herbivoros (sauries with bird pelvis), to which belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa finde is a primitive theropode.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in Tawa's skull, researchers found signs of air bags, such as those also owned by the descendants of the theropodes, the birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa he also finds the bones of the spine were evidently filled with air partially.
Tawa is the most ancient and primitive air bag theropode, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the later giant sauropods also possessed air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers deduce that the Sauries emerged there for the first time.
Therefore, the three genealogical lineages were separated at the beginning and spread from South America through all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a unique earthly mass, the Pangea supercontinent.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa the remains of two other theropodes not very closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single related predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe at least three waves of migration to North America, Alan Turner from the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are opponents as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, who belongs to a brother group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonn Martin Sander's paleontologist.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils continue to be preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains a riddle.
Meanwhile, in the Triasic the dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of the present crocodiles and the pterosaurus and with many other sauries.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship extinct on the edge of the Triassic towards the Jurassic.
Successful stories weren't eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a massive extinction that dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could defeat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact stopped the boom of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triasic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
