In a state of vigil, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of mentally ill people and drug addicts, the limits between imagination and reality vanish.
As long as it happens during the dream, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with closed eyes, we can unhinderedly surrender ourselves to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, who experiences sleep-like states during the vigil, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often considered in the modern Western world as crazy or drug addict, or at least as a maniac.
But such images and voices not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drug addicts.
The blame has our imagination: the same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes make the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality undibushed.
Onionically modified alert states can appear in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases we call them visions, and in the worst, madness.
