75 per cent of working mothers have had work problems because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women from younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundad and career of women in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the field of work due to maternity.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of couple life and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an out-of-home activity, work part-time, or have an unstable job, start conviving with a couple before, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and maternity, and have less offspring.
"Women between 35 and 49 years of age with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after cohabitation, which increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their vital trajectory to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and arrival of the children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on maternity although less on the schedule of matching," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they marry and have the first birthplace.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the older the age they marry and the first child.
The difference is also maintained between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those with elementary and higher education have been mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 on average, respectively.
"A further division between women is established depending on their level of study.
While those who have elementary studies get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those at medium or higher levels invest this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a pre-marriage condition and the arrival of a child," Delgado details.
