Emergency braking aid is already mandatory
As with anti-locking ABS brakes and passing through with ESP stability control, emergency braking support systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all newly enrolled light commercial cars and cars, while for the rest a period of deficiency is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians, although, by its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency braking assistant is doing more pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver's tray.
But he doesn't always keep that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the car component manufacturer Bosch, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not reached the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, however, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four would be avoided with harm to people - when the so-called smart emergency braking system is popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, as well as acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps you increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
